Articles.Content:
KSPI-E imprived FTL drive is already fully capable to fly to nearby stars at 100 times the speed of light. Note this will not be easy as it requires heavy Warp Drives and vast amount of power.

If that's too fast for you, their are already exisitng Slower Than Light solution like the Magnetic Confinement Reactor fitted with a Magnetic nozzle which is capable of reaching 1.200.000s

Note that in the near future I plan to add a Deadalus ICFE drive to KSPI-E which is a STL drive specialised for Interstellar travel. THe primary fuel/propellant will be Deteurium / Helium 3 which can be collected in large quantities from the Larger Gas Planets. Uranus will be best for this. Then You can travel to nearbour start in the galaxtic neighbourhood within a year under time acceleration

I'm not sure what I need to provide in order to help progress/get support, but I tried running this mod on 1.0.5 last night.

In a game with, this mod (both the latest and dev branche) with Kopernicus - 0.6 (the latest available on CKAN) and OPM 1.9.2 everything loads fine.  I can go to the tracking station and zoom out and see the other solar systems.

Everything goes well until I launch into orbit, and go to map mode and try to plot maneuver node.  When I exit the map mode my ship overheats and explodes.

The concept behind this mode is awesome and I would love to see it working on 1.0.5 and future releases.

ETA: The boom only occurs, if I zoom out beyond the default sol system.

I don't really know what is going wrong, but basically:

ksp can have only 1 "active star", kopernicus has a feature that can change the "active star" while playing.

you can see this if you zoom out from the tracking station, you will see that the light effect will bounce from the sun to other stars depending on which star is closer to the camera

the problem is that, if you are controlling a ship and then manage (usually by zooming out) to make kopernicus change the "active star", when the " "active star" status comes back to the sun (or whatever star you are closer to in that moment) the parameters of the star that define power generation and overheating are not loaded correctly (I imagine) and then the ship blows up.

so I had to set the "luminosity" of all stars in GN to zero, in order to avoid the overheating to occur.

this fix will not affect the aestetics of the stars and illumination of planets, just the power generation and overheating of crafts

of course if anyone finds a better solution I will be happy to implement it
